"&#xa0;\nWritten Evidence (USA 04): Xenia Dormandy, Chatham House&#xa0;\nXenia Dormandy is the Project Director of the US \nProgramme\n and the Acting Dean of the Academy for Leadership in International Affairs at Chatham House.  From 2009-2011, she was the Executive Director of the \nPeaceNexus\n Foundation in Switzerland.  Prior to this, Xenia was Executive Director of Harvard Kennedy School’s \nBelfer\n Center for Science and International Affairs, Director of the Project on India and the Subcontinent, and a member of the Board of the \nBelfer\n Center.  From 2001-05, Xenia worked at the US State Department on issues from nonproliferation, to homeland security and South Asia.  She also spent six months helping to set up the Homeland Security Office in the Office of the Vice President, and was Director for South Asia at the US National Security Council. \n&#xa0;\nSummary&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nTo what extent has the UK’s foreign policy approach to the US changed under the Coalition Government, and with what results for UK national interests, especially with respect to areas of unique UK-US cooperation?&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhat is the relationship between the UK Government’s policy towards the US and its increased focus on UK relationships outside the Transatlantic area?&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nHow is the UK Government responding, and how should it respond, to the US ‘pivot to Asia’?&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nHow, in its relations with the US, should the UK Government build on the lessons of post-2001 interventions involving both states in third countries? \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n22\nth\n August 2013\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n"